1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,500
Mark, you have to talk to me, Mark.

2
00:00:03,500 --> 00:00:04,500
Six.

3
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:06,500
I need to fix this before I go.

4
00:00:06,500 --> 00:00:08,500
I have no idea when you're coming back.

5
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:11,500
Five main engines start.

6
00:00:11,500 --> 00:00:14,000
Can you have told her you were going to save the world?

7
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:15,000
No.

8
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:16,000
Four.

9
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:17,500
And you become a parent.

10
00:00:17,500 --> 00:00:18,500
Three.

11
00:00:18,500 --> 00:00:20,500
One thing that comes really clear.

12
00:00:20,500 --> 00:00:22,500
Two.

13
00:00:22,500 --> 00:00:25,500
And I just didn't want to make sure your children feel safe.

14
00:00:25,500 --> 00:00:26,500
One.

15
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:33,000
I'm coming back.

16
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:42,000
Well, what we found was, you know, the further out into the infinite, we went and the more we isolated these characters,

17
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:45,000
so we have to go across the universe.

18
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:53,000
The more the focus naturally becomes on their humanity, you know, on that intimate bond they have,

19
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:55,000
what makes us human, all those issues.

20
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:07,000
I think there's something about the starkness and the massiveness of the environment that really reduces this focus very tightly to human bonds and what makes us who we are.

21
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
With the robot, we sort of said, let's do the absolute minimalist thing.

22
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Let's say he's a piece of gear like, you know, a tripod or a camera dolly or something,

23
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:17,000
not something that's supposed to look like a human being.

24
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:21,000
So he has a personality, the great billow, and you know, puts into the thing.

25
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:25,000
He was the guy puppeteering a robot, doing the voice of the robot.

26
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:30,000
And great personality, I think, shines through, but the actual design is very, very utilitarian.

27
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
It's really just about function.

28
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:34,000
And the spaceships are the same.

29
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:39,000
We didn't want to have any sense of design to them, particularly no, you know, futurist design.

30
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:46,000
We really wanted to look at what's been used in space, what's been used on the Apollo missions, on the space shuttle, on the ISS,

31
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:50,000
and every switch does what it needs to do, and every button does something.

32
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,000
And, you know, all the docking mechanisms, all those things.

33
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:57,000
We're all just based on contemporary reality of how do you deal with life in space?

34
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:01,000
What we were able to do is look back, and this is something I like doing,

35
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:06,000
sort of looking back at the great achievements of the past, and avail ourselves of those techniques.

36
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:10,000
So miniature work, motion control, things like that, they pioneer.

37
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:15,000
But then combining that with today's technology, which allows you to composite things in a particular way.

38
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:20,000
UCG, in a particular way, to enhance those types of effects.

39
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:26,000
So we really tried to build on what's been done before, but add our own techniques to it.

40
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
And there are quite a few things in the film that have never been done before, and may never be done again.

41
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:42,000
I don't know, but certainly mixing and varying our techniques, using some old, some new, I think helps really disguise the trickery involved in the film.

42
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:47,000
Because obviously it's all, you know, artificial at the end of the day, but it felt real to us making it,

43
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:51,000
and hopefully it feels real to the audience watching it.

44
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:55,000
Do not go gentle into that good night.

45
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:00,000
Old age should burn and rave a closer day.

46
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:05,000
Rage, rage against the dying of the light.

47
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:08,000
All right, are you ready? Yes, you are.

48
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:17,000
We all find a way that we always have.

